               <interp inst="t18460202-411" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18460202"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18460202-411" type="date" value="18460202"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18460202-411-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-411-18460202 t18460202-411-offence-1 t18460202-411-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>411. <persName id="def1-411-18460202" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-411-18460202" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-411-18460202" type="age" value="22"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-411-18460202" type="surname" value="CLARK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-411-18460202" type="given" value="FREDERICK"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">FREDERICK CLARK</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18460202-411-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18460202-411-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18460202-411-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="theftFromPlace"></interp> for stealing 1 pump, value 15<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18460202-name-1018" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1018" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1018" type="surname" value="WATNEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1018" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460202-411-offence-1 t18460202-name-1018"></join>Daniel Watney</persName>, in a barge on the <placeName id="t18460202-geo-13">
                        <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18460202-411-offence-1 t18460202-geo-13"></join>river Thames</placeName>.—2nd <hi rend="smallCaps">COUNT</hi>, for stealing 83lbs. weight of copper, 14<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and 20lbs. weight of metal, 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; and that he had been before convicted of felony.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DOANE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1019" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1019" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1019" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1019" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WILLIAMS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a lighterman, in the service of Daniel Watney, who has a wharf at Wandsworth—his premises all join—I had charge of a lighter belonging to him on the 3rd of Feb., 1845—I had a copper pump and a bucket there—I saw them safe between six and seven o'clock the night before, and next morning the barge was gone—I found it at Battersea Reach—I got on board, and missed the pump and bucket—in my judgment the copper now produced formed that pump and bucket.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1020" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1020" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1020" type="surname" value="BOORE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1020" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES BOORE</persName>
                  </hi>. I am shopman to Lambert and Son, brass-founders, New Cut, Lambeth. I received this metal bucket from Mrs. Somers on the 3rd of Feb., 1845—I delivered it to Reed on the 5th of Feb.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1021" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1021" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1021" type="surname" value="SPINKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1021" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS SPINKS</persName>
                  </hi>. In Feb., 1845, I was in the service of Mrs. Somers, a coppersmith. On the 3rd of Feb. I received some copper which has formed a pump—it was brought by Hosier and Hadley who have been convicted—there was a third man outside, who was dressed something like a coal-heaver—he</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184602020182"></xptr>
               <p>had very little whiskers—he was about the same size as the prisoner; but it he is the man, he is so altered that I cannot recognise him—I afterwards gave the copper pump to the officer—I think 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 14<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. was paid for it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1022" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1022" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1022" type="surname" value="MERRY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1022" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN MERRY</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable V</hi> 70.) I received nine pieces of copper from Mr. Spinks, at Mrs. Somers's shop.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1023" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1023" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1023" type="surname" value="SAUNDERS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1023" type="given" value="JOHN CHARLES HEATH"></interp>JOHN CHARLES HEATH SAUNDERS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a millwright in the employ of Mr. Watney—this bucket is his property.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1024" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1024" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1024" type="surname" value="EMERSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1024" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS EMERSON</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant V</hi> 16.) I was at the police-station at Clapham on the 12th of Jan., when the prisoner was brought in in custody—I told him what he was charged with—he said he was outside, While Richard Hosier and Thomas Hadley were taking these things—I read the warrant to him—he said nothing then—about a quarter of an hour after, when I went to the cell and gave him two sacks to cover over him, he said, "It was a bad job—I was with them, I shall get transported the same as they are," or "as well as they are" that he must take the rough with the smooth, he could not help it now—he said he had been living at all parts of London since that—I told him Hadley and Hosier were transported, one at Croydon, and one at the Central Criminal Court.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> It appears there were two men tried for this crime? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I am not aware that there is a reward for the apprehension of any person who committed that robbery—I never asked the foreman any questions—I did not take down the words the prisoner repeated—I have a good memory—I was not at the former trial—I do not know that the prisoner had been drinking—he had not the appearance of it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1025" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1025" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1025" type="surname" value="ELLIOTT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1025" type="given" value="HENRY JAMES"></interp>HENRY JAMES ELLIOTT</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 13th of Jan. I was locked up in the station—I was charged with spending some money, but I was not convicted—the Magistrate dismissed me by letting me pay the money—I was in the same cell where the prisoner was on the 13th—I said to him "What are you in here for?"—he said, "Stealing a pump"—he said, "There was a pump stolen from Mr. Watney's, at Wandsworth, twelve months ago"—I said, "Were you in the mess?"—he said, "Yes; the other two mates got trans<lb></lb>ported ten years each: one was from Croydon, the other the Old Bailey," but, says he, "I <hi rend="italic">hooked</hi> it; I was a full-whiskered man then, but I shaved my whiskers all off"—he said it was a bad job, he had no doubt but what he should get <hi rend="italic">lagged</hi> for it, he must make his mind up to that; it was a bad job, he could not help it now—he said he should not have been taken if he had not come on that side of the water to help his sister move—that he had a bed on his head when the policemen came to him, but he gave the policemen a two hours' run, and then gave them an <hi rend="italic">upper</hi> and a <hi rend="italic">downer</hi> before they took him—I had no quarrel with him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Will you repeat exactly what this man stated on the 13th of Jan.? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I asked him what he was in there for—he asked me what I was in for—I told him I was never locked up in a gaol before—the money I spent was for work done at the Wandsworth Railroad—it belonged to me and some more men—they gave me orders to take it—the Magistrate allowed me my liberty on condition of repaying the money, because the men were agree<lb></lb>able to it—I have been at work at the reservoirs in Battersea-fields—I worked before that for Mr. Thornton, at Nine Elms—I do not know what I am to have for my trouble in coming here—I asked Mr. Paynter whether I should be paid my expenses—he said, "Yes, when you go to the Old Bailey."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1026" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1026" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1026" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1026" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>ROBERT SMITH</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant L</hi> 21.) I apprehended the prisoner on the 12th of Jan., in Broad-wall, Christ church, Surrey—he had a bed on his head—I had been looking after him for about three months—I asked if his name was Frederick Clarke—he denied it, and said it was William Bryant—I took</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184602020183"></xptr>
               <p>him to the gas-lamp, and recognised him—as we were going along, he ran away—I had a quarter of an hour's good hard run after him—he ran up a street which was no thoroughfare, and two gentlemen caught him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1027" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1027" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1027" type="surname" value="GRIFFIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1027" type="given" value="JAMES WILLIAM"></interp>JAMES WILLIAM GRIFFIN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Thames-police inspector.</hi>) I have known the pri<lb></lb>soner about eight years—he wore whiskers about twelve or fourteen months ago—I know both Hosier and Hadley—I have seen the prisoner in their company at different times—the last time was about two years ago, when they were on the river—I have been on the look-out for the prisoner for twelve months.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18460202-name-1028" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1028" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1028" type="surname" value="KING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18460202-name-1028" type="given" value="HENRY JOSEPH"></interp>HENRY JOSEPH KING</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Thames police-constable, No.</hi> 30.) I produce a cer<lb></lb>tificate of the prisoner's former conviction at this Court—(<hi rend="italic">read Convicted</hi> 31<hi rend="italic">st Jan.</hi>, 1842, <hi rend="italic">and confined three months</hi>)—I was at the trial—the prisoner is the person.</p>
